# Schema Management & Flyway

**Flyway owns the schema. Hibernate only validates it.**

## Core Principles
- All schema changes (tables, indexes, constraints, seed data) MUST be in Flyway migrations
- Hibernate must NOT create or modify schema — use `ddl-auto=validate` in production
- Never use `@Index` in JPA entities — define indexes in Flyway migrations
- Lookup table seed data (enum values) should be inserted via Flyway migrations

## What Flyway Manages
- Table creation and alterations
- Index creation (including partial, expression, and concurrent indexes)
- Constraints (unique, check, foreign key)
- Seed data for lookup/enum tables
- Any PostgreSQL-specific DDL

## Why Not `@Index` in Entities
- `@Index` only works with `ddl-auto=create/update` (unsafe for production)
- Cannot express PostgreSQL-specific indexes (partial, expression, concurrent)
- No version history or audit trail
- Not reviewable by DBAs

## Migration File Convention
- Location: `src/main/resources/db/migration/`
- Naming: `V<version>__<description>.sql` (e.g., `V1__create_tables.sql`, `V2__add_indexes.sql`)
- Each migration is immutable once applied — never edit existing migrations
